{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_horsetail_ver01/data/sn86075141/00340582032/1938012701/0700.xml":{"full_text":"Montana Labor News\nfr\nThe American standard of\nliving must be maintained\nin order that American in\nstitutions may not be sub\nject to perils of discontent.\nThere can be no prosperity\nwithout justly high wages.\nEarnings of working people\nare the basis and index of\nprogress in any community.\nPUBLISHED WEEKLY IN THE INTERESTS OF ORGANIZED LABOR\nBUTTE, MONTANA, THURSDAY, JANUARY 27, 1938\nVol. XIII\nNo. 48\nJOINT LEGISLATIVE COMMITTEE OF\nUNIONS AND PROGRESSIVES TO MEET\nIN MUSICIANS HALL FEBRUARY 4TH\nDuplicate Your Card\nFor Social Security\nButte, Montana Old-Age Insur\nance Office to Aid Workers\nWho Have Lost Social Secur\nity Account Cards.\nCommercial and industrial work\ners who have lost their Social Se\ncurity account number cards may\nnow obtain duplicates from Social\nSecurity Board Field Offices of\nwhich there are 17 in the states of\nArizona, Colorado, Idaho, Montana,\nUtah, and Wyoming, it was learned\ntoday.\nThis service to workers who have\nlost their cards has been established\nto help them obtain employment,\nsaid Stewart J. Thomas, manager,\nthe board's Butte, Montana Field\nOffice, Bureau of Old-Age Insur\nFormerly duplicates of ac\nance.\ncount number cards issued in con\nnection with the Federald old-age\ninsurance program could be obtained\nonly from Washington.\nWorkers in Silver Bow and near\nby counties of Beaverhead, Broad\nwater, Deer Lodge, Gallatin, Gran\nite, Jefferson, Lake, Madison, Min\neral, Missoula, Ravalli, and Sanders\nmay now obtain duplicates, upon\nproper identification at the Butte\nfield office, at 402 Silver Bow Block,\nMr. Thomas said.\n\"Reports from all parts of the\ncountry indicate,\" he explained,\n\"that employers are giving prefer\nence to job applicants having ac\ncount number cards. This may be\ndue to the fact that if a worker\nfails to obtain an account number\nthe employer must, under Federal\nTreasury regulations, apply for a\nnumber for this worker. The em\nployer is required to include both\nthe worker's name and his account\nnumber in periodic reports of the\nworker's wages which he files with\nthe Treasury.\n\"We have been instructed to ob\ntain the home address and the name\nand address of the employer of per\nsons requesting duplicate cards. This\ninformation is required so that, if it\nis found necessary, the board can\ncommunicate with the wage earner\nor his employer,\" Mr, Thomas con\ncluded.\nDELEGATES TO TRADES COUNCIL ENJOY\nTHE ANNUAL INSTALLATION FESTIVITIES\nMASS MEETING HELD\nTO RELIEVE DISTRESS\nWilliam Dunn Gives Dramatic\nAddress; Auditorium Filled.\nBill Dunn thrilled almost a thou\nsand people Sunday, January 23rd,\nat the old Butte High School audi\ntorium at a mass meeting when he\naccused the corporate and monopoly\ninterests of the United States of\nAmerica of attacks upon the Presi\ndent of the United States such as\nthis nation has not witnessed since\nthe Civil War and probably not in\nits entire history. Mr. Dunn de\nfended the present administration in\nits efforts to perfect a plan of re\nform that would at least relieve the\ndistress brought on by the selfish\nness of the monopoly capitalists. He\nwas roundly applauded.\nThe speaker read statistics show\ning the extent of the profits of some\nof the major corporations and then\ncompared them with the wages and\nmaterial conditions of the common\npeople. The greater part of his dis\ncourse was devoted to the attempt\nof the present democratic adminis\ntration to control the ruthlessness\nand selfishness of the corporations.\nAfter listening to the talk no one\nwith a reasonable mind could be in\ndoubt as to the avowed purpose of\nthe ruling cU.ss of the country to\neither establish a dictatorship of\ntheir own or else crash the temple\ndown about their heads as Sampson\ndid in the biblical story.\nThe relief demands were present\ned by Elmer Fredrickson. These de\nmands were presented to the Works\n(Continued on Page 6)\nUNFAIR\nCLERKS UNION and\nSILVER BOW TRADES\nAND LABOR COUNCIL\nFAMOUS GROCERY\n336 S. Montana St.\nPlans for 1938 Campaign to Be\nOutlined; Deserters Are Con-\ndemned.\nDue to the unsatisfactory results\nobtained in the matter of labor leg\nislation in the past by representa\ntives who 1\nbeen endorsed by\nin has been devised\nLabor, a ne\nby Sam S S .4, prominent labor\nleader and g' ority floor leader of\nthe House epresentatives of the\n25th legi' e\nit is inte 5\nmore acti v? irt in politics through\nout the\nsession, whereby\nthat Labor take a\nand attempt to sup\nas upon whom they can\nsupport of legislation\nlenefit the masses.\nport cam\nrely in\nwhich i\nA br\n.\u25a0trospect of the political\nsituation m the past will not be\nHeretofore labor organiza\namiss.\nlions have refrained from taking a\ntoo prominent part in state politics\nand in some cases have left the se\nlection of representatives and sena\ntors to the entrenched interests or\nto certain selfish individuals who\nhave waxed fat at public expense.\nIn the campaign of 1934, there\nwas organized in Silver Bow Coun\nty a Farmer-Labor group whose\navowed intention was to pick a sen\nator and representatives who would\ntruly represent the will of the peo\nple. This organization chose as its\ncandidates men from the various\nlabor unions and two from farm\norganizations. The slate was en\ndorsed by the Silver Bow Trades\nand Labor Council and all other or\nganizations affiliated with the group.\nBut unfortunately many labor or\nganizations did not take this move\nment seriously enough to refrain\nfrom asking individual endorse\nments of individuals who aspired\nfor these same offices. Due to this\nfact, the original slate was broken;\nbut the five original Farmer-Labor\ncandidates who were elected had\nenough influence upon the others\nso that Silver Bow County was rep\nresented by nine men who returned\nwith a batting average of 100 per\ncent fbr labor legislation. The\nothers had their usual 25 per cent.\nBecoming flushed with the suc\ncess of their previous experiment,\nand believing that a similar cam\npaign would carry on of its own\nmomentum, the labor unions in the\ncampaign of 1936 became careless\n(Continued to Page 6)\nMembers of the Silver Bow\nTrades and Labor Council,\nFriends, Guests and Children\nCelebrate With Songs, Music,\nand Cheer; Bill Palmer Acts\nAs Major-Domo.\nFollowing a brief business session,\nthe Silver Bow Trades and Labor\nCouncil last Tuesday celebrated its\nannual installation of officers with\nsong, music, vaudeville and refresh\nments. William Palmer acted as\nchairman of the occasion and was in\nhis glory. Palmer is never so happy\nas when contributing to the mirth\nand happiness of his fellow associ\nates. His enthusiasm was only\nequalled by the pep and energy of\nEddie Price, floor leader and singing\ndirector. The occasion will long be\nremembered as an outstanding social\nevent of union circles. Many of the\nmost talented members of the Mu\nsicians Union were present and were\nrepeatedly given encores for their\nperformances. The children in the\nprogram drew round after round of\napplause.\nThe Bishops School of Dancing\nwas complimented for the excellent\nmanner in which its pupils enter\ntained. Following is the social pro\ngram as outlined by Bill Palmer.\n1. Tap dance by Darlene Sylvester.\n2. Accordian solo and tap dance by\nIrene Duckham. 3. Tap dance trio\nby Lillian Merkle, Alma George,\nand Bobby Whisiel. 4. Solo by\nButte's boy tenor, Jack Mitchell.\n5. Russian dance by Dell Crail, Lois\nShone and Dolores Shone. These\nlatter two are daughters of A1\nShone, the attorney. This part of\nthe program was all arranged\nthrough the 'cooperation of Mr.\nBishop of Bishops School of Danc\ning. The delightful manner in which\nthese children carried on their work\nwas captivating and the audience\nrepeatedly expressed its apprecia\ntion. Music for the songs and danc\ning of the children was furnished\nby Miss Catherine O'Keefe. In fact,\nMiss O'Keefe served as accompanist\nfor all of the amateur program.\nThe second section df the enter\ntainment began with Mary Lou\nConnors singing several popular and\nsemi-classical songs. Her voice was\nappealing and winsome. She was\ncalled back several times. Paul\n(Continued on Page 0)\nOREGON FARMERS ISOLATED BY FLOOD WATERS\nK v\n-'P*\n\nOne of many farm homesteads on the outskirts of Portland which were endangered by raging waters\nfollowing the rise of nearby streams after a series of heavy rainstorms in the northern part of the state.\n(Federated Pictures)\nThe floods caused much property damage and marooned many families.\nWHAT'S HAPPENING IN THE UNIONS\nIn terminating his tenure of office\ni president of the Silver Bow\nTrades and Labor Council, James\nComba expressed his sincere appre\nciation of the attitude of the dele\ngates toward him during the past\ntwo years, and complimented them\nupon their determination to hold the\nunion movement together in face of\nalmost insuperable obstacles and\nprovocations for dismemberment.\nThe retiring president thanked all\nof his committees for their coop\u00e9ra\ntion. He said the Silver Bow Trades\nand Labor Council had shown the\npeople in Silver Bow County and\nthe state of Montana the way to\nsolidarity and the value of cohesion\nin the ranks of labor. Mr. Comba\nrefused to re-run for office and was\nsucceeded by Charles Davis of the\nTeachers. Following his farewell\nremarks, the new officers of the Sil\nver Bow Trades and Labor Council\nwere installed. The names were\npublished in last week's Montana\nLabor News.\nA communication came from the\nButte Miners Union stating that a\npublic meeting will be held at the\nMiners Union hall February 10, 1938,\nat 7:30 p. m., in the interest of Tom\nMooney. All unions are asked to\nparticipate with the Miners Union\ncommittee in staging this event and\nmaking it a success. All interested\nin the cause of human freedom are\nrequested to attend.\nGeorge Neal sent in an urgent\nappeal for funds for the Sunshine\nCamp. He explained the remark\nable work that had been done to\nhelp under-par children. The letter\nstated that $3,400 was needed to\nclear up the title of land purchased\nfor a camp site near the Nine Mile.\nThe Sunshine camp began in 1930.\nIt has all modern conveniences, in\ncluding electric lights, telephone,\nwater under pressure and a staff of\nattendants. It is closed down in the\nwinter with exception of a care\ntaker. The Trades and Labor Coun\ncil felt so kindly toward the project\nthat they gave a contribution.\nA communication was submitted\nby the committee appointed to work\nin the interest of retaining the\nswimming pool and other physical\nfacilities at the old Butte High\nSchool for the interest of the \u00abhil\ndren of the whole community. The\ncommunication submitted by the\ncommittee requested the Silver Bow\nCouncil to send a delegate to the\nmeeting of the School Board and\ndeliver the message of the Council.\nThe delegates were in accord with\nthe proposition outlined by the com\nmittee. Miss Ann Golubin is one\nof its active members.\nDelegate John Mullaney and\nchairman of the Relief Committee of\nthe Silver Bow Trades and Labor\nCouncil said that acute distress is\nbeing experienced by the people of\nSilver Bow County owing to the\nshutdown of the mines and the in\nability of the WPA to put them to\nwork. Mr. Mullaney mentioned that\nthere are about 500 people now cer\ntified for relief with no jobs avail\nable for them. He then mentioned\nthat $200,000 was tied up at the\nState Capitol at Helena and the\nTrades and Labor Council should do\nsomething to have this money re\nleased. The Trades and Labor Coun\ncil sent a communication to the state\ngovernment and also to the repre\nsentatives of the national Senate\nand House to increase the quota for\nMontana.\nElsewhere in this issue is an ur\ngent appeal to patronize the Roose\nvelt Ball which will be held Janu\nary 29 at the Winter Garden Ball\nRoom. The Silver Bow Trades and\nLabor Council urged all of its af\nfiliated unions and all of its affili\nated members to buy tickets for this\nevent. Delegate Comba pictured the\nneed of assisting the President and\nthe Georgia Foundation in aiding\nthe work,\n\nThe Grievance Committee of the\nTrades and Labor Council brought\nin a report placing the Famous\nGrocery of 336 South Montana\nStreet on the unfair list, A notice\nto that effect is carried on the front\npage of this issue,\nThe Silver Bow Trades and Labor\nCouncil is notifying the Billings or\nganizations that they are working\nwith them in respect to placing cer\ntain state merchants on the unfair\nlist, but owing to contracts now\nexisting between different unions\nand these firms it is difficult to force\nthe boycott in certain areas,\n\nThe Laundry W-vkers Union re\nported that Frank Donovan was re\ncently elected president of the\nLaundry Workers organization suc\nceeding Joe White, who has served\nin that office during the past year.\nAll of the former officers of the\nLaundry Workers Union were re\nelected.\nThe Fire Fighters National organ\nization with the assistance of Maur\nice Mulcahy of Butte, who has been\nserving as International Representa\ntive of Montana, reported that there\nare now seven locals within the state\nof Montana, which are located at\nButte, Helena, Missoula, Anaconda,\nGreat Falls, Billings, and Kalispell.\nThe Musicians Union has been\nnegotiating with KGIR about the\nplacing of musicians in the studio\nrooms to furnish musie for the pro\ngrams. This plan originated in the\ninternational office of the Musicians\nand the National Broadcasting Sys\ntem. The Musicians felt that they\nwere entitled to have some of their\nmembers work in the studio rooms\ninstead of having radio stations pre\nsent so many records and other me\nchanical music to the radio audience.\nNegotiations are now proceeding\nalong that line. The matter, how\never, has been referred to the\nTrades and Labor Council and at\nthe present time has been taken out\nof the hands of the Musicians Union\nand centered in the Central Labor\nCouncil.\nANTIQUATED PHRASE\nIn these days of laying waste\nwhole cities and the inhabitants\nthereof, the term \"cannon fodder\" is\nsomething of an understatement. It's\nlike the difference between fodder\nfor one plow horse and a whole\ndrove of elephants.\nANNOUNCEMENT\nThe Butte unit of Labor's\nNon-Partisan League will meet\nat the Carpenters Union hall\nnext Thursday, Feb. 3rd, 8 p.\nm. Union members and other\npersons who are interested in\npromoting progressive legisla\ntive action are urgently in\nvited to participate in this\nmeeting. Permanent officers\nwill be elected and considera\ntion given to the question of\ncalling a state meeting, as well\nas immediate organizational\nproblems.\nThe Butte unit has been rec\nognized by the national office\nof Labor's Neu Partisan\nLeague and is authorized to\nproceed as a bona fide or\nganization.\nWALTER CARRINGTON,\nChairman Pro Tern.\nMISSOULA UNIONS ARE\nCAUSTIC IN ASSAILING\nALIEN CONTRACTORS\nMISSOULA.\u2014A strike has been\nin progress since December 29, 1937,\non the St. Regis bridge work, be\ncause the contractor stubbornly re\nfuse? to recognize both the unions at\nSuperior and Missoula. An out-of\nstate contractor bid the job in much\nlower than any Montana contractor,\napparently with the intention of im\nporting cheap labor to do the work.\nIt is generally recognized that work\non a bridge job requires mostly\nskilled or semi-skilled men, very\nfew common laborers are used.\nQuite a number of truck drivers are\nbeing used on the St. Regis job. The\nchief objection of the contractor to\nthis particular project is the wage\nscale of the steel construction work\ners. Neither does he want to pay\nthe scale to the pile driving crews.\nThe regular wage scale for this type\nof work is $1.25 an hour and it is\nreported that the contractor is try\ning to chisel this down to 75 cents\nper hour.\nThis job should call the attention\nof all Montana people and especially\nthe unions to the menace of per\nmitting contractors from out of the\nstate bidding on public and private\nwork in Montana. Very little fault\nhas been found with Montana con\ntractors. These other firms come in\nhere and bring with them the low\nwages and miserable conditions of\nmany of the other states and Wash\nington contractors are notorious in\nthis regard. From good authority it\nis learned that 35 men were import\ned from Spokane by this contractor\nand that only three men were used\nfrom Mineral County.\nThe contractor on this job has ap\nplied to the Bureau of Public Roads\nfor an extention of time, alleging\nthat he has been held up on account\nof labor trouble and bad weather.\nThe bureau should recognize that\nMontana has had the finest kind of\nwinter weather this year than the\npast decade. Not only that but men\nin the county are in sore need of the\nwork. The Teamsters Union at\nSuperior, a branch of Local 448 at\nMissoula, has tied up the job since\nthe strike was inaugurated. They\nare determined that it is going to\nbe held up until the work is 100\nper cant organized for all the crafts.\nMissoula extends to all its friends\nand supporters in Mineral County\ntheir sincere appreciation for help\ngiven them in their effort to make\nbetter conditions on this job. Busi\nness men in this area now realize\nthat the more money the people\nmake the more money they will\nhave to spend. In contrast to the\nSt. Regis job is the one at Nimrod,\nabout 35 miles east of Missoula. This\ncontract is being done with all Mon\ntana labor, and every one is receiv\ning union wages and working under\nunion conditions. James Crick is\nthe contractor.\nIt is expected that within a short\ntime the underpass at Missoula will\nbe let soon. Missoula people are\nhopeful that the work will be given\nto a Montana contractor who has\nbeen taught in union principles and\nwho will not try to chisel on the\nworkers. The name of the contrac\ntor on the St. Regis job is George\nLyon.\n\"It would be far worse (than los\ning millions of dollars in trade) if\nfailure to invoke the neutrality act\nshould involve us in a war that is\nof no concern of ours.\"\u2014Rochester\n(N. Y.) Times-Union.\n\"The French-Canadian people are!\nnot behind the Duplessis padlock!\nlaw.\"\u2014Robert L, Calder, K. C., dis\ntinguished attorney of French-Cana-|\ndian stock.\nSHORTER HOURS AND WAGE PROTECTION\nURGED BY GREEN TO EASE RECESSION\nA. F. of L. President Also Includes Larger Federal Appropriations\nfor Unemployment Relief, Expansion of Public and Private\nHousing Programs, and Extension of Social Security Benefits\nin Plans Presented to Senate Unemployment Committee.\nBy A. F. of L. News Service.\nIn marked contrast to the welter of visionary and impracticable reme\ndies for the existing business recession presented to the Senate Commit\ntee on Relief and Unemployment by government officials, business execu\ntives and economists, were the sound and constructive measures urged by\nPresident William Green of the American Federation of Labor.\nEmphasizing the tremendous increase in unemployment during the last\nfew months which has raised the number of jobless workers to between\neight and ten millions, Mr. Green declared that \"unless effective measures\nare promptly taken we are faced with a real threat of the current reces\nsion developing into another and more serious chronic business depres\nsion.\"\n\"The critical situation we are now facing present\u00ab a real challenge to\nour Congress, to our Federal government and to our entire nation,\" Mr.\nGreen said.\n\"The time has come when the country must resort without hesitation\nto legislative means of checking the recession and re-establish the re\ncovery on a sounder and firmer basis.\n\"In undertaking any such measures, Congress must not lose sight of\nthe great need\u2014the need to look beyond the exigencies of today's emer\ngencies so that we can build for long-\nrange economic and industrial sta\nbility in the future.\"\nPresents Seven-Point Program\nAfter thoroughly analyzing the\nbusiness recession in all of its\nphases, with special consideration of\nthe necessity of nation-wide co-op\neration of all groups to meet the\ncrisis, Mr. Green proposed the fol\nlowing remedies which, he said,\n\"must be applied without delay in\norder to be fully effective\":\n\"(1) Shortening of the hours of\nwork through maximum hour regu\nlation in industrial employment.\n\"(2) Maintenance of existing wage\nstandards.\n\"(3) Continuation of the public\nworks program on an extended\nscale and establishment of adminis\ntration of public works on a perma\nnent basis for the purpose of long\nrange planning to meet future emer\ngencies.\n\"(4) Extension of the public low\nrent housing and slum clearance\nprogram by additional appropriation\nof funds and through the suspension\nof the present requirements for lo\ncal contributions.\n\"(5) Further stimulation of home\nconstruction by private enterprise\nthrough remission of local taxes for\na limited period of time.\n\"(6) Revision and broadening of\nthe Social Security program: to pro\nvide for a nation-wide system of un\nemployment compensation; to ex\nContinued on Page 6)\nMORE MONEY NEEDED TO FIGHT INFANTILE\nPARALYSIS; IS CLEARLY SHOWN BY FIGURES\nWASHINGTON, D. C.\nIf you\nwant to know how bitterly money\nis needed for the fight on infantile\nparalysis, take a map of the United\nStates, a bunch of black headed pins,\nand a small tube of white paint.\nStick a black headed pin in each\nof 11 states: Maine, New Hampshire,\nVermont, Mississippi, South Dakota,\nNorth Dakota, Wyoming, Idaho, Ne\nvada, Arizona and New Mexico. In\nthese 11 states, THERE IS NO OR\nTHOPEDIC HOSPITAL.\nNow take your tube of paint and\nput a little white streak across the\nheads of 7 pins. Stick one of these\nin each of the following states: North\nCarolina, South Carolina, Arkansas,\nIowa, Montana, Utah, and Oregon.\nThe\u00abe are the states which have\nONE orthopedic hospital each.\nHospital Totally Inadequate\nNow, take pencil and pad and\nWorld Almanac, and do a little look\ning up and figuring. You will find:\nThat there are 776,000 square\nmiles in the states which have\nNO orthopedic hospital, NO up\nto date facilities for treating in\nfantile paralysis. This, roughly,\nis 6 times the size of Italy and\n3% times the size of France.\nRecovery Long Process\nDoes it need anything more to\nmake you see that the United States\nas a whole, is terribly short of places\nr\nWINTER GARDEN DANCE HALL\nSaturday Evening, Jan. 29th\n\u2014For the Benefit of\u2014*\nINFANTILE PARALYSIS SUFFERERS\nEndorsed by the Organized Labor Movement and\nthe Silver Bow Trades and Labor Council. The\npublic is urgently requested to respond to this\nnoble cause.\nLABOR CONCILIATOR\nARRIVES IN BILLINGS\nA dispatch from Billings states\nthat picketing of the Hart-Albin\nstore has been abandoned and\nFrank Wenig, labor conciliator of\nthe United States Department of\nLabor, is there arranging a meet\ning of employers and employees\nin regard to wages and working\nconditions.\nThe Associated Industries ap\nparently are not taking very\nkindly to the activities of the labor\norganization and are resisting ef\nforts of collective bargaining.\nFree Townsend Social\nAt the Y. Friday Night\nTownsend Club No. 1 will hold its\nregular monthly social Friday eve\nning at the Y. M. C. A. and invites\nall friends of the members and the\nmovement to attend.\nA musical program, talks by ex\nponents of the Townsend plan, and\nrefreshments are promised by the\nsocial committee, through its chair\nman, Mrs. M. McKay.\nMr. M. J. Mulholland will preside\nat a business meeting preceding the\nsocial.\nto treat infantile paralysis?\nOf course, infantile paralysis pa\ntients are shipped across state lines.\nBut that does not alter the terrible\nshortage of proper places for treat\nment shown by your map.\nRestoration from infantile paraly\nsis is usually a long and therefore a\ncostly process. A long journey\ndoesn't lessen that cost a bit.\nSpecial Attention Vital\nWith the single exception of\nGeorgia Warm Springs Foundation,\nno orthopedic center specializes on\ninfantile paralysis alone. They must\ntreat every kind of physical handi\ncap.\nInfantile paralysis needs special\nattention. A general orthopedic cen\nter can provide this special atten\ntion which needs special knowledge,\nspecial training and often special\napparatus\u2014if it has the price. It\nneeds dollars, dollars,, dollars to\napply to practical, specific pro\ngrams.\nThe National Foundation for In\nfantile Paralysis will provide these\ndollars\u2014with your help.\nThe President's Birthday Ball cele\nbration on January 29 and the Birth\nday Greeting to the President will\nraise funds for the Foundation. Or\nganized labor throughout the nation\nwill cooperate in the Birthday Balls\nand the Greeting.","height":"19914","width":"14685"}}
